{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517821"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12837"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12837"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.15,0.34,0.08,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76493"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5280"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61990"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"3535"},{"type":"tags","id":"3874"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"9763"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9301"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76493"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with persisting left hip pain for several months. She has recently noticed a deformity in her left leg. She has a history of hearing loss and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications include metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her left leg is deformed and bowed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal alkaline phosphatase 690 U/L (100-420). An X-ray of her left femur shows thickened and sclerotic cortex with a cottonwool appearance. A bone scan demonstrates multiple foci of increased tracer uptake in the skull, left shoulder, left hemipelvis, and proximal left femur (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Single dose intravenous zoledronic acid","Intramuscular calcitonin for six months","Oral risedronate for two months","Intra-articular glucocorticoid injection","Total hip arthroplasty"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Paget disease of bone, including bone pain, deformity, elevated alkaline phosphatase, and characteristic radiological findings. The bone scan shows multiple areas of increased uptake, indicating polyostotic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose intravenous zoledronic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment. It is the most potent bisphosphonate available and has been shown to achieve the highest rates of biochemical remission with a single dose. The medication works by inhibiting osteoclast activity, thereby reducing the accelerated bone turnover characteristic of Paget disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular calcitonin\u003C/strong\u003E was historically used but is now considered second-line therapy due to its lower efficacy, need for repeated administration, and higher cost compared to bisphosphonates. While it can reduce bone pain and turnover, its effects are temporary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral risedronate\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for Paget disease but is less potent than zoledronic acid. It requires a longer duration of therapy and has lower remission rates. Additionally, compliance with oral bisphosphonates can be challenging due to strict administration requirements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntra-articular glucocorticoid injection\u003C/strong\u003E might temporarily relieve joint pain but does not address the underlying bone disease. It is not an appropriate first-line treatment for Paget disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal hip arthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E may eventually be needed if severe osteoarthritis develops, but surgery is not first-line treatment. The underlying metabolic bone disease should be treated first with bisphosphonates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of hearing loss in this patient is significant as it is a common complication of skull involvement in Paget disease. Treatment with bisphosphonates may prevent further progression of hearing loss by controlling disease activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous zoledronic acid is the most effective bisphosphonate for Paget disease of bone.","Key features of Paget disease include elevated alkaline phosphatase, bone pain, deformity, and characteristic radiological findings.","Hearing loss is a common complication of skull involvement in Paget disease."],"references":["Bouchette P, Boktor SW. Paget Disease. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2022 Jul 11]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430805/","Britton C, Walsh J. Paget disease of bone. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2012;41:100-3. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/march/paget-disease-of-bone"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61990"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12837"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20189"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20189"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f9fc9b38-4d14-42bb-a8d0-bc3bc7467b48.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f9fc9b38-4d14-42bb-a8d0-bc3bc7467b48.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":530,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61990"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T14:43:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T14:43:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5280"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76493"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6